# No silent deferrals

When implementing an approved plan, ticket, or handoff: **do the whole scope**. Do not mark items DEFERRED, "follow-up", "partial", "if feasible", or "ship later" unless the user **explicitly** says to defer that piece in this conversation.

## Default

- Plan / acceptance matrix / todos = **must ship** in this pass.
- Soft plan language ("if feasible", "optional", "document partial") is **not** permission to skip. Treat it as **do it**; only the user's clear "defer X" / "skip X" / "not this slice" overrides.
- Finishing early by writing a verify-log DEFERRED section instead of code is a **failure**.

## Allowed deferrals (only these)

1. User said so in this thread (quote their words in the verify note).
2. Hard external blocker (no GPU, missing secrets, Workbench down) — **stop and ask**; do not invent a follow-up ticket and call it done.
3. Out-of-scope listed in the plan's **Out of scope** section (not soft options inside Scope).

## Forbidden

```text
❌ "Compute cull DEFERRED — follow-up T-xxx.8.1"
❌ Shipping CPU path only when the plan also required WebGPU compute
❌ Closing todos as completed while leaving gated work undocumented-as-deferred
❌ Asking "want me to do the rest?" after marking the slice shipped
```

```text
✅ Implement every Scope / acceptance-matrix row
✅ If blocked: ask once, wait — do not tag ship
✅ Defer only after user: "defer compute cull" / "skip W8 compute"
```

## Interaction with Mode A/B/C

This rule does **not** authorize Cursor to write app code. It means: when **you** (or Claude via handoff) are executing a plan, **do not drop gated items**. Cursor Mode B handoffs must not pre-authorize "document as deferred" for in-scope work.
